<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="200" name="Some Basic Concepts of Chemistry">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Anything that has mass and occupies space is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Matter</option><option id="B">Energy</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental definition of physical substance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>SI unit of amount of substance is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mole</option><option id="B">Gram</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One of the 7 base SI units.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>SI unit of temperature is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kelvin (K)</option><option id="B">Celsius</option><option id="C">Fahrenheit</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absolute scale used in science.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Law of Conservation of Mass was given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lavoisier</option><option id="B">Dalton</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Value of Avogadro's Number (N_A) is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6.022 x 10^23</option><option id="B">1.66 x 10^-24</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Entities per mole.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>1 amu is equal to ____ grams.</text>
            <option id="A">1.66 x 10^-24</option><option id="B">6.022 x 10^23</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass of 1/12th of C-12 atom.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formula mass of Water (H2O) is ____ u.</text>
            <option id="A">18</option><option id="B">20</option><option id="C">16</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2(1) + 16 = 18.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molar mass of Oxygen gas (O2) is ____ g/mol.</text>
            <option id="A">32</option><option id="B">16</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass of 1 mole of diatomic oxygen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of 1 mole of an ideal gas at STP is ____ L.</text>
            <option id="A">22.4</option><option id="B">11.2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Molar volume constant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Smallest particle of an element that retains its properties is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Atom</option><option id="B">Molecule</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Building block of matter.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A mixture having uniform composition throughout is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Homogeneous</option><option id="B">Heterogeneous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Salt solution.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship: 0 degrees Celsius = ____ Kelvin.</text>
            <option id="A">273.15</option><option id="B">32</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Temperature offset.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Law of Definite Proportions was given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Joseph Proust</option><option id="B">Gay-Lussac</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>A compound always contains same elements in fixed ratio by mass.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pure water from any source has H:O ratio of ____ by mass.</text>
            <option id="A">1 : 8</option><option id="B">2 : 1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2g H per 16g O.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Law of Multiple Proportions was given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dalton</option><option id="B">Aristotle</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Explains formation of CO and CO2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of significant figures in 0.0025 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">5</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leading zeros are not significant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of significant figures in 100.0 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trailing zeros with decimal are significant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Precision refers to ____ of various measurements.</text>
            <option id="A">Closeness</option><option id="B">Accuracy</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consistency of results.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Accuracy refers to closeness of measurement to ____ value.</text>
            <option id="A">True / Accepted</option><option id="B">Previous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Correctness of results.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Empirical formula of Benzene (C6H6) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CH</option><option id="B">C2H2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simplest whole number ratio.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molecular formula of Glucose is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">C6H12O6</option><option id="B">CH2O</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actual number of atoms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molarity is moles of solute per ____ of solution.</text>
            <option id="A">Liter</option><option id="B">Kilogram</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unit: mol/L (M).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molality is moles of solute per ____ of solvent.</text>
            <option id="A">Kilogram</option><option id="B">Liter</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unit: mol/kg (m).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reagent that is completely consumed in a reaction is ____ reagent.</text>
            <option id="A">Limiting</option><option id="B">Excess</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Determines the amount of product.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Percent by mass = (Mass of solute / ____) x 100.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass of solution</option><option id="B">Mass of solvent</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Concentration term.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mole fraction is the ratio of moles of a component to ____ moles.</text>
            <option id="A">Total</option><option id="B">Solvent</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dimensionless quantity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sum of mole fractions of all components in a solution is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 (Unity)</option><option id="B">100</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mathematical property.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gay-Lussac’s Law of gaseous volumes is valid when gases are at same ____.</text>
            <option id="A">P and T</option><option id="B">Volume</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Volumes react in simple whole number ratios.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of moles (n) = Given mass (w) / ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molar Mass (M)</option><option id="B">Density</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard mole calculation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of molecules in 1 mole of CO2 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6.022 x 10^23</option><option id="B">3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Independent of molecule complexity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass of 1 mole of Carbon atoms is ____ g.</text>
            <option id="A">12</option><option id="B">6</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>By definition of mole.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equivalent weight of an acid = Molecular weight / ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Basicity</option><option id="B">Acidity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Number of replaceable H+ ions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equivalent weight of a base = Molecular weight / ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acidity</option><option id="B">Basicity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Number of replaceable OH- ions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normality (N) = Number of ____ of solute per liter of solution.</text>
            <option id="A">Gram equivalents</option><option id="B">Moles</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relates concentration to reactivity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A gas at STP occupies 22.4 L. This amount is ____ mole(s).</text>
            <option id="A">1</option><option id="B">2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Molar volume at standard conditions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of a substance is mass per unit ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Volume</option><option id="B">Area</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Units: g/cm^3 or kg/m^3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemical formula for table salt is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">NaCl</option><option id="B">KCl</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sodium Chloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Atomic mass of Helium is ____ u.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 protons + 2 neutrons approx.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The SI unit 'Candela' measures ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Luminous intensity</option><option id="B">Electric current</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One of the 7 base units.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A balanced chemical equation obeys the law of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conservation of Mass</option><option id="B">Multiple proportions</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Atom counts must match on both sides.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Mole fraction of ethanol in a mixture of 46g ethanol and 54g water is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.25</option><option id="B">0.5</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>n_eth = 46/46=1. n_wat = 54/18=3. x = 1/(1+3).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of 0.1 M HCl required to neutralize 10 mL of 0.1 M NaOH is ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">10</option><option id="B">20</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>M1V1 = M2V2 for 1:1 reaction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass of one atom of Carbon-12 is ____ g.</text>
            <option id="A">1.99 x 10^-23</option><option id="B">12</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>12 / (6.022 x 10^23).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which concentration term is independent of temperature?</text>
            <option id="A">Molality</option><option id="B">Molarity</option><option id="C">Normality</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass doesn't change with temperature, but volume does.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ratio of atoms in 4g Hydrogen to 16g Helium is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 : 1 (2 mol H? no 4g H=4mol H. 16g He=4mol He.) Ratio is 1:1? wait atoms? H is H2? 4g H is 2mol H2 = 4mol H atoms. 16g He is 4mol He atoms. Ratio 1:1.&lt;/text&gt;
            &lt;option id="B"&gt;2 : 1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on mole calculation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of moles in 4.4g of CO2 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.1</option><option id="B">0.01</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>4.4 / 44 = 0.1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equivalent weight of H2SO4 (MW=98) in typical acid-base reaction is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">49</option><option id="B">98</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>98 / 2 (dibasic acid).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Percentage of Oxygen in NaOH (MW=40) is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">40</option><option id="B">20</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(16 / 40) x 100.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of significant figures in 500.00 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">3</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Decimal point makes trailing zeros significant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A compound contains 50% element A (At.wt=10) and 50% B (At.wt=20). Empirical formula is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">A2B</option><option id="B">AB2</option><option id="C">AB</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relative moles: A=50/10=5, B=50/20=2.5. Ratio 2:1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A sample of gas occupies 100 L at 1 atm. Volume at 2 atm (const T) is ____ L.</text>
            <option id="A">50</option><option id="B">200</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Boyle's Law P1V1 = P2V2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specific gravity of a liquid is ratio of its density to density of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Water</option><option id="B">Air</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dimensionless ratio.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass of 11.2 L of CO2 at STP is ____ grams.</text>
            <option id="A">22</option><option id="B">44</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>0.5 moles x 44 g/mol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Average atomic mass of Chlorine (Isotopes 35 and 37 in 3:1 ratio) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">35.5</option><option id="B">36</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(35x3 + 37x1) / 4.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>How many grams of NaOH are present in 250 mL of 0.5 M solution?</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">10</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Moles = 0.5 x 0.25 = 0.125. Mass = 0.125 x 40.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of 1g of Hydrogen at STP is approx ____ L.</text>
            <option id="A">11.2</option><option id="B">22.4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1g H is 0.5 moles H2. 0.5 x 22.4.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>One mole of CH4 contains ____ atoms of Hydrogen.</text>
            <option id="A">24.08 x 10^23</option><option id="B">6.022 x 10^23</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 mol CH4 has 4 mol H atoms. 4 x N_A.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of electrons in 18 mL of water (d=1g/mL) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">10 N_A</option><option id="B">18 N_A</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>18 mL = 18g = 1 mol. One H2O has 10 electrons (8+2).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A gas mixture contains H2 and O2 in 1:4 mass ratio. Molar ratio is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4 : 1</option><option id="B">1 : 4</option><option id="C">8 : 1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>H2 moles=1/2. O2 moles=4/32=1/8. Ratio (1/2):(1/8) = 4:1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molality of pure water (d=1g/mL) is ____ mol/kg.</text>
            <option id="A">55.5</option><option id="B">18</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1000g / 18g/mol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of significant figures in result of (2.5 + 4.50) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 (Result 7.0)</option><option id="B">3</option><option id="C">1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on least decimal places (2.5 has 1).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between Molarity M and Molality m involving density d: m = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1000M / (1000d - M*Mwt)</option><option id="B">M / d</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Interconversion formula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is an intensive property?</text>
            <option id="A">Density</option><option id="B">Mass</option><option id="C">Volume</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Doesn't depend on system size.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is an extensive property?</text>
            <option id="A">Enthalpy</option><option id="B">Temperature</option><option id="C">Pressure</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Depends on amount of substance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Max number of molecules among: 44g CO2, 48g O3, 8g H2, 64g SO2?</text>
            <option id="A">8g H2 (4 moles)</option><option id="B">44g CO2 (1 mol)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Calculate moles for each.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Law of reciprocal proportions was given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Richter</option><option id="B">Berzelius</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Explains ratios when elements combine with a third.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard for atomic weights is isotope ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbon-12</option><option id="B">Oxygen-16</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chosen by IUPAC in 1961.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ratio of masses of Carbon in CO and CO2 for fixed mass of Oxygen is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 : 1</option><option id="B">1 : 2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>O:C in CO is 16:12. In CO2 is 32:12 -&gt; 16:6. For 16g O, C is 12 and 6. Ratio 2:1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>One microgram is ____ kilograms.</text>
            <option id="A">10^-9</option><option id="B">10^-6</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>10^-6 g = 10^-9 kg.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of protons in 1 nmol of H+ ions is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6 x 10^14</option><option id="B">1 x 10^9</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 mol has 6e23. 1 nmol has 6e23 x 1e-9.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Atomic mass unit 'u' was formerly called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">amu</option><option id="B">Dalton</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unified atomic mass unit.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>STP conditions currently defined by IUPAC: 0 C and ____ bar.</text>
            <option id="A">1 (100 kPa)</option><option id="B">1.01325 (1 atm)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Modern standard (22.7L vs old 22.4L).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vapor density of a gas is ____ half of its molar mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Always</option><option id="B">Sometimes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>VD = M / 2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Percent Oxygen in CaCO3 (MW=100) is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">48</option><option id="B">16</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>48 / 100.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>One mole of electrons has mass approx ____ mg.</text>
            <option id="A">0.55</option><option id="B">1.0</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>N_A x 9.1e-31 kg.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Limiting reagent in: 2H2 + O2 -&gt; 2H2O given 4g H2 and 32g O2?</text>
            <option id="A">None (Stoichiometric mix)</option><option id="B">H2</option><option id="C">O2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 mol H2 reacts with 1 mol O2. Mix is exactly 2:1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mole fraction of solute in 1 molal aqueous solution? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.0177</option><option id="B">0.1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 / (1 + 55.5).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of water is max at ____ K.</text>
            <option id="A">277</option><option id="B">273</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>4 degrees Celsius.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following contains most atoms? 1g Ag, 1g Mg, 1g O2, 1g Li?</text>
            <option id="A">1g Li (Atomic wt = 7)</option><option id="B">1g Mg</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Largest number of moles (lowest At.wt).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of neutrons in 7mg of 14C isotope is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2.4 x 10^21</option><option id="B">6 x 10^23</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>7mg = 0.5 mmol. 0.5e-3 x N_A x 8 neutrons/atom.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>A gaseous mixture contains H2, He, CH4 in mass ratio 1:2:4. Molar ratio? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 : 2 : 1</option><option id="B">1 : 1 : 1</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>(1/2) : (2/4) : (4/16) -&gt; 0.5 : 0.5 : 0.25 -&gt; 2:2:1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Max mass of H2O produced by 10g H2 and 64g O2? ____ g.</text>
            <option id="A">72</option><option id="B">90</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>4g H2 + 32g O2 gives 36g H2O. Scaling gives 72g (O2 is limiting reagent? no 64g O2 needs 8g H2. 10g H2 available. O2 limiting. 64g O2 gives 72g H2O).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Weight of residue when 10g CaCO3 is heated strongly? ____ g.</text>
            <option id="A">5.6</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">4.4</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>CaCO3 -&gt; CaO + CO2. 0.1 mol CaCO3 gives 0.1 mol CaO = 5.6g.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If N_A was 1.0 x 10^23, mass of one mole of Nitrogen gas would be ____ g.</text>
            <option id="A">4.65 (28 * (1e23/6.02e23))</option><option id="B">28</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mole scale shift.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of 0.1 M KMnO4 required to oxidize 100 mL of 0.5 M FeSO4 in acidic medium? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">100 mL</option><option id="B">500 mL</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>n-factors: KMnO4=5, FeSO4=1. 5 x 0.1 x V = 1 x 0.5 x 100.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mole fraction of solvent in a solution where x_solute = 0.2 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.8</option><option id="B">0.2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 - 0.2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of 2M solution of substance A (MW=100) is 1.2 g/mL. Molality is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1.67</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass of 1L solution = 1200g. Mass solute = 2x100=200g. Mass solvent = 1000g = 1kg. Molality = 2/1 = 2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation state of Cr in K2Cr2O7 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+6</option><option id="B">+7</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2(+1) + 2x + 7(-2) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A gas is 14 times heavier than Hydrogen. Atomic weight if diatomic? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">14</option><option id="B">7</option><option id="C">28</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>VD=14, MW=28. M2 = 28 -&gt; M=14.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In the reaction 3MnO2 + 4Al -&gt; 3Mn + 2Al2O3, 1 mole of Al reduces ____ mol MnO2.</text>
            <option id="A">0.75</option><option id="B">1.33</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio 3/4.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specific heat of metal is 0.06 cal/g. Approx atomic mass (Dulong-Petit)? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">107</option><option id="B">60</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>6.4 / 0.06 approx 106.6.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of atoms in 0.1 mole of P4 is ____.</text>
